# make sure you are in your project folder (not just ~)
cd /path/to/your/project

# initialize Git (if not already done)
git init

# link your GitHub repo (if not already linked)
git remote add origin git@github.com:Rakshita-Goyal/practise.git

# add all files in this folder
git add .

# create the very first commit
git commit -m "Initial commit"

# rename current branch to main
git branch -M main

# push to GitHub
git push -u origin main


o actually commit and push your changes, do this step by step:

# 1. Add all files in your folder to staging
git add .

# 2. Commit with a message
git commit -m "hello"

# 3. Push to GitHub
git push -u origin main


See the commit history
git log

This shows:Commit hash, Author, Date, Commit message

#last commit done 
git show --stat

#git show : detailed changes in last commit
git show

#to show one line each of each commit
git log --oneline

#to initialize to user name and email
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"

#to chack the setting or what is done till now
git config --list
Git shows all the configuration values that are currently active on your system.
System level → applies to all users on the computer
Global level → applies only to your user account (~/.gitconfig)
Local level → applies only to the current repository (.git/config inside your project)

#to show urls git is using now
git remote -v
rakshitagoyal@Rakshitas-MacBook-Air practise % git remote -v
origin	git@github.com:Rakshita-Goyal/practise.git (fetch)
origin	git@github.com:Rakshita-Goyal/practise.git (push)


#git pull origin main
git pull → fetch changes from a remote repo and merge them into your current branch.
origin → the default name for your remote GitHub repository (you added this when you did git remote add origin ...).
main → the branch you want to pull changes from (usually the default branch on GitHub).

#git fetch origin main
git fetch origin main

Downloads the latest commits from the remote (origin/main)
Does NOT merge them into your current branch
Your local branch stays unchanged, but you now have the updated remote info

rakshitagoyal@Rakshitas-MacBook-Air practise % git pull origin main
bFrom github.com:Rakshita-Goyal/practise
 * branch            main       -> FETCH_HEAD
Already up to date.
rakshitagoyal@Rakshitas-MacBook-Air practise % git fetch origin main 

From github.com:Rakshita-Goyal/practise
 * branch            main       -> FETCH_HEAD


#to show state of currect directories working in
git status

